    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-08-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-08-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="251"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d251">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">717.2114/52</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-08-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 31, 1927</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received September 19.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 464</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With no instructions or comment from the
                    Department to refer to in connection with my telegram No. 181 of July 28, 4
                    P.M., I have the honor to advise the Department that I have nevertheless
                    discussed this entire question informally with President Diaz and intimated that
                    I saw no reason why preliminary negotiations with the Colombian Minister should
                    not be undertaken. I am informed that this has been done. I hope my action in
                    the matter will have the approval of the Department. It would, however, be
                    appreciated by both President Diaz and this Legation if the Department would
                    indicate whether a settlement along the lines proposed by the Department in its
                    instruction No. 212 of March 25 [<hi rend="italic">21</hi>], 1925,<note n="65"
                        xml:id="d251fn65">
                        <ref target="frus1925v01#pg_431">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1925, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 431</ref>.</note> still seems advisable
                    to the Department, or what, if any, additional representations and points might
                    be brought up in negotiations tending toward the settlement of this old
                    question.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles C. Eberhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
